Supply data analysis

What is the supply to demand dynamic and do they match?

1. Undersupply

The coverage ratio tells us something about missed demand-side opportunities, but in the ridesharing business, not all hours of the week are created equal. Low coverage ratios are far more detrimental to the business when combined with high absolute numbers of unique users that saw zero cars. Given the data that we have on hand, we do not know a few things:

  1. we do not know if the same unique users that saw 0 cars later saw 1+ cars in the same hour
  2. we do not know if two or more unique users have the app open simultaneously and intend to ride together in the same car

For this analysis, then, we will consider all unique users that saw 0 cars as missed trips. The boxplots below ( + indicates the mean, while the box portion indicates 25th and 75th percentiles) show the distribution of absolute missed trips across the entire time period, aggregated by hour and day of week. Immediately, we can make seveal observations about when trips are being missed:

  • morning (8:00-10:00 ) and evening (17:00-20:00) peak commute periods on weekdays

  • early morning (2:00-5:00) hours on weekends

  • Friday nights (18:00-23:00)

demand = read.csv("OverviewSearch.csv")
supply = read.csv("DriverActivity.csv")

colnames(demand) = c("date", "saw_no_car", "saw_car", "rounded_coverage_ratio")

Even during the horus of peak demand, there are still drivers waiting around for bookings

This observation tells us that, at peak demand periods, idle drivers should be directed to the geographical hotspots of demand in order to maximize existig supply. Unused supply is an important factor to consider when formulating a method to calculate undersupply. Based on a constant RPH coefficent, we are making the assumption that usused supply can be diverted to meet demand while nonexistent supply hours cannot. From here, we can devise a formula to calculate undersupply and stack rank hours of the week by their average rate of missed trips per hour.

Real Undersupply Rate (RUR) =

total missed trips - (waiting hours * RPH)


RUR rests on the assumption that usused supply can be optimized to address missed trips and that shifting supply hours should prioritize filling nonexistent supply gaps. For example, if in a given hour, there are 10 missed trips and 5 hours of waiting with RPH of 2, the RUR = 0 trips/hour. Compare this to 10 missed trips and 2 hours of waiting time, where RUR = 6 trips/hour.


wes = supply[supply$dow %in% c("Sun","Sat"),]

neworder <- c("Sat","Sun")
supply_copy = supply # make copy of supply data
supply <- arrange(transform(wes,
                            dow=factor(dow,levels=neworder)),dow)

We will add a column rur to the existing supply table and then calculate the mean RUR aggregated by weekday and hour to find the top 36 hours per week of undersupply.

merged = merge(x = supply, y = demand[ , c("saw_no_car", "ts")], by = "ts", all.x=TRUE)
colnames(merged)[13] = 'missed_trips'

merged$rur = merged$missed_trips - (merged$rph * merged$waiting)

sample_supply = cbind(merged[2], hour(merged$ts), merged[12], merged[13], merged[7], merged[10], merged[14])
colnames(sample_supply)[2] = 'hour' 

ss_sorted <- head(sample_supply[order(-sample_supply$rur),])

kable(ss_sorted, row.names = F) %>%
  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>%
  column_spec(7, bold = T, background = "#ffa343")

3. Visualization of undersupplied hours

The heatmap below uses the mean RUR aggregated by hour and day of week, which can be shown to drivers to guide their online time schedule.

merged = merge(x = supply_copy, y = demand[ , c("saw_no_car", "ts")], by = "ts", all.x=TRUE)
colnames(merged)[13] = 'missed_trips'

merged$rur = merged$missed_trips - (merged$rph * merged$waiting)

sample_supply = cbind(merged[2], hour(merged$ts), merged[12], merged[13], merged[7], merged[10], merged[14])
colnames(sample_supply)[2] = 'hour'

sample_supply$dow = as.character(sample_supply$dow)

#aggregate rur by hour and day of week

df2 = sample_supply %>%      
  dplyr::group_by(hour, dow) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(mean_rur = mean(rur, na.rm=TRUE)) 

dummy = df2  #create dummy dataframe to fill with NA values

df2 = as.data.frame(head(df2[order(-df2$mean_rur),], n =36))
df2$dow = as.character(df2$dow)
dummy$dow = as.character(dummy$dow)

diff = as.data.frame(dplyr::setdiff(dummy,df2)) # take difference between both dataframes and use diff to create NA values for heatmap
diff$mean_rur = NA

df2 = rbind(df2, diff) #combine dataframes

neworder <- c("Mon","Tue","Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun")
df2 <- arrange(transform(df2,
                         dow=factor(dow,levels=neworder)),dow)


ggplot(df2, aes(hour, dow)) + 
  geom_tile(aes(fill = mean_rur), colour = "black") + 
  geom_text(aes(label = round(mean_rur, 1)), na.rm = TRUE, size=2.5) + 
  scale_fill_distiller(palette = "Oranges", direction = 1, na.value="white") +
  scale_x_discrete(name ="hour", 
                   limits=c(0:23)) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.key.width = unit(2, "cm"),
        panel.grid = element_blank()) + 
  coord_equal() + 
  theme(text = element_text(family="Avenir")) +
  ggtitle("Heatmap of RUR (Real Undersupply Rate)", subtitle = "top 36 undersupply hours from 2016.11.14 - 2016.12.18 ")
